tweet: 23/ The battle for the App Store isn‚Äôt some cutesy isolated issue.  It is a +$100s billion-per-year type of fight.  It is an important part of the distribution model in entertainment and more productivity, and importantly ‚Äì how we interact with each other on a daily basis.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 22/ In a sit-down interview, Elon postulated that North America has no WeChat equivalent.  WeChat is an ‚Äúeverything‚Äù app in China that is chat, social, and payments all wrapped into one.  He thinks Twitter might be able to do this.  This will cause all sorts of headbutting.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 21/ Elon is now coming in and introducing subscription tiers ($8/month verification), as well as talking about building a payment layer on top of Twitter.  This comes from his background of building out Paypal.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 20/ Now it's Elon‚Äôs Turn and I think this one has the potential to get very interesting.  The pre-musk era of Twitter was so incredibly boring as there were no major changes to revenue streams and essentially no change in the underlying product.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 19/ Epic aimed to get the court to allow third-party app stores to get apps on iOS devices, but largely lost the lawsuit, then appealed.  Apple won the antitrust suit but was ordered to allow developers to add in-app links to outside websites where payments could be accepted.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 18/ The Games v. Apple saga started in 2020 when allowed Fortnite players to make purchases directly in-app, skirting the in-app purchase rules.  Apple quickly pulled the Fortnite app from the App Store and was ready with an antitrust lawsuit over the Store rules.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 17/ Another major contention here is the 30% take rate on IAP (in-app purchases).  Every movement needs a champion - the battle against Apple has lately been led by Epic Games (Fortnite ) CEO, Tim Sweeney. Fortnite is a very popular game with ~80M active users on a monthly basis.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 16/ This led to many apps trying to circumvent the in-app purchase model altogether.  Netflix and other entertainment apps will not let you subscribe from within the app, and some have resorted to a 30% price hike on subscriptions when done within apps rather than on a website.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 15/ Apple has strict rules surrounding how users get content from within apps and how that benefits them.  Until recently, Apps purchased from the App Store, any in-app purchase, and subscriptions made within an app all had to pay a 30% cut to Apple.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 14/ Apps fit into a wide variety of pricing schemes.  Some apps are free while others feature a one-time cost associated with downloads.  Ads support some apps, and reoccurring subscription charges or other in-app purchases support others.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 13/ As of 2022, there are more than 1.2B iPhone users and 1.6M apps available.  In 2022, the App store brought in $72.3B in revenue for Apple, up from $38.7B in 2017.  For reference, Netflix did $31B in revenue over the last 12 months.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 12/ The App Store can best be described as a gated or closed platform with a massive install base.  The App Store is the only way you can get access to a wealthy cohort of end users and you have to pay the toll to make money.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 11/ The lower the take rate, the more attractive it is to come onto to platform for the supplier, the higher the take rate, the higher the value capture for the platform owner.  Very powerful platforms can charge higher take rates.  These are the basic tenants of a platform.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 10/ Platforms derive their value from how large they can grow their user base (supply and demand side) and how many transactions are performed on the platform.  They then make their money taking a portion of this transaction as a fee (rake or take-rate).  https://t.co/lWPlqqji2t
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 9/ Once you reach a frame of inertia, you have to pay equal attention to curating and growing both demand and supply - and the most important thing is combining high volume with a fair and modest take rate.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 8/ At the heart of this is the concept of the Network Effect.  The Field of Dreams phrase ‚ÄúIf you build it, they will come‚Äù comes to mind meaning you have to build out an attractive supply-side product first for demand to even show up in the first place.  https://t.co/bmd3v9UsL5
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 7/ Fostering an environment that is very supplier-friendly goes hand in hand with this.  You need to have great actors on the system selling great products that further increase demand.  More demand = better sellers = more demand = better sellers‚Ä¶ and so on‚Ä¶
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 6/ There is a virtuous flywheel inherently built into platform models.  As you aggregate demand, better suppliers will come to your marketplace in order to target a very specific user base that already desires that particular solution.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 5/ But the concept of a platform is just a fancy way of saying marketplace.  An arena that connects buyers and sellers.  To build out a successful platform you need to have proper incentive structures to foster healthy growth of both the demand and supply side of the marketplace.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 4/ With the proliferation of the internet and software companies, we experienced the evolution of a business model known as a ‚Äúplatform‚Äù.  Platforms aimed to be one-stop shops where you have a landing zone of sorts with a bunch of other stuff built on top of it.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 3/ Yeah, absolutely, they made the damn thing! But 30%?  C'mon now‚Ä¶  This is due to the strength of the platform product that they have built.  App developers don't HAVE to go on the App Store, but they should.  Let‚Äôs start by breaking down the strength of the Platform Model.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 2/ Apple is the closest thing to a gatekeeper when it comes to the modern internet.  For ages, they have been taking a cut through the app store on everyone that has generated revenue through an app on an iPhone.  Do they deserve a cut of every dollar generated on an iPhone?
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: There‚Äôs no doubt Elon is the ‚Äúman in the arena‚Äù.  But it looks like he‚Äôs entering a new Arena and this time - against a towering Goliath.  Apple‚Äôs 30% toll on access to a massive wealthy cohort has been one of the most defensible monopolies of the modern era.  Can it stand? üßµ
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Blackstone‚Äôs redemption limit being hit is a definitive sign that the real estate market is slowing, and the outlook for real estate investing is not good.  I‚Äôll keep following the story and keep you updated on what happens.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Every redemption lowers the fee that Blackstone collects for managing the fund.  They also collect 12.5% of the returns, with a 5% hurdle.  Blackstone‚Äôs stock is down because both the management and the performance fees are expected to be lower.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: There‚Äôs one other factor to consider here: Blackstone doesn‚Äôt just make money from the performance of the fund.  They also make a management fee of 1.25% per year, paid monthly.  Even if the fund returns zero, Blackstone gets about $862 million a year for running the fund.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: A majority of the fund is in apartments (about 55%)  The housing market is slowing down, which we‚Äôve known for several months.  Here‚Äôs how the fund is invested:  https://t.co/yNHSDTAbUF
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: But could the fund be in serious trouble?  The cost to borrow has obviously risen this year, so the fund won‚Äôt be able to aggressively purchase apartments and industrial buildings like it has over the past 5 years.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: But the redemption limit being hit could be a sign that the fund‚Äôs performance is in trouble.   Investors are nervous that others are pulling their money out because the fund won‚Äôt do well going forward.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Blackstone shares are down about 7% on this news.  Coincidentally, BREIT accounts for about 7% of Blackstone‚Äôs assets under management.  So what‚Äôs the market worried about?  Redemptions aren‚Äôt the problem. Blackstone can limit those to avoid a ‚Äúrun on the bank‚Äù scenario.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Blackstone is able to limit withdrawals to avoid having to liquidate real estate assets suddenly.  The limits are 2% of NAV monthly or 5% quarterly.  The quarterly limit has now been exceeded, so Blackstone can limit how much money investors are able to pull out.  https://t.co/QtpThbvqvI
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: So what‚Äôs going on with the fund now?  This week, Blackstone announced the fund had hit its quarterly withdrawal limit.  Too many investors are trying to pull their money out at once.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: The fund is only sold to wealthy investors through select financial advisers and isn‚Äôt available to the general public.  Their website says that 3-year annualized returns are 15.5% with a 4.4% distribution rate.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Blackstone Real Estate Income Trust (BREIT) is a real estate investment trust that invests in apartments, industrial, retail, and hotels.  It‚Äôs one of the largest real estate funds in the world, even though it only started in 2016.

tweet: Sam's feed just cut out in the middle of a sentence.

tweet: Q: "What do you see as your future?"  Sam: "I don't know what my future is...A lot of it's not in my hands at this point. I want to helpful to regulators to help FTX customers."

tweet: Q: "Can I ask you about the drugs?"  Sam says he had his first sip of alcohol after his 21st birthday, and he has "half a glass of alcohol a year".   He says there were no 'wild' parties or rampant drug use at FTX.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Now he's asking about the infamous real estate purchases.   He says that his parent's property was "intended to be the company's property" and they just happened to stay there while they worked with the company.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Q: "Your parents are law professors. What did you tell them when this all happened?"  Sam: "I called them and said 'I think there might be a problem here'".
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Now Sam is asked about his meeting with SEC Chairman Gary Gensler, and whether or not he felt he needed to buy his way into those meetings.  Sam said it's not about "buying" or "donating", but it's more about influence and navigating bureaucracy.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Now he's asked about his donations to the Democratic party and his lobbying efforts.  Sam says that their main effort was to get permission to offer leveraged trading products to customers in the US.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Sam is asked about the infamous Twitter DMs that were made public where Sam basically said that his effective altruism was a facade.  He says that he does want to help people, but he also says companies do a lot of "bullsh*t" to look good.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Andrew asks if hundreds of millions were stolen from the exchange as FTX collapsed.  Sam says he had already been cut off from systems by then and couldn't have done it, and doesn't know who did.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: We've zeroed in on Nov. 7th being the day where "everything shifted." Before then, Sam believed everything was fine. But on that day, he worried that FTX and Alameda were in trouble.  However, he tweeted that FTX doesn't invest customer funds on that day (he later deleted it)
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Q: "How much are you concerned about criminally liability at this point?"  Sam stutters for a few seconds, then says that's not what he's focusing on. "There will be a time and place to think about my own future."

tweet: Q: "Are you in the Bahamas because you think you can't leave?"  Sam: "I've been in the Bahamas for the last year."  Q: "Do you think you could go to the US?"  Sam: "I think I could."
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Q: "What are your lawyers telling you right now? Do they suggest this is a good idea to be speaking?"   Audience laughs  Sam: "No, they are not...But I do have a duty to help customers out"
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Again, Sam says he "wasn't nearly cautious enough" and didn't anticipate the extent to how correlated all of his assets were and how quickly everything could collapse.

tweet: But Sam insists that those efforts were to help the industry as a whole, and not to keep FTX or Alameda liquid.  He says those deals had little effect on Alameda's trading positions.

tweet: Now Andrew asks about the comparisons between SBF and JP Morgan earlier this year - specifically if his deals to bail out BlockFi and others were an effort to keep the price of FTX Token (FTT) up

tweet: But by November 6th to 7th, Sam said he realized that FTX might also be in trouble as the comingling of funds became more clear.

tweet: Andrew asks what Sam was nervous about.  "I was nervous that it would lead to massive losses for Alameda" - Meaning that Alameda's margin trades were in danger. But he wasn't concerned about FTX at all early in November.

tweet: Andrew asks when Sam first knew FTX had a problem.  He says November 6th (which was 5 days before they filed for bankruptcy.  "I could see a run on the bank starting...I was nervous" Sam says.

tweet: Andrew says FTX "flouted Know Your Customer laws", but Sam shoots back that customers still had to go through KYC onboarding, even if the funds weren't going directly to FTX.

tweet: Sam says that FTX and Alameda had always comingled funds, since FTX used Alameda's bank accounts when the exchange first started in 2019.

tweet: Andrew keeps asking Sam a specific question about the amount of comingling of funds, when it started, who did it, etc.  Sam won't answer directly and just says that he didn't give the proper oversight.

tweet: Q: "When did the comingling of assets being?"  Sam: "I think the [margin] position got substantially higher during 2022"

tweet: But Sam says he moved out of the penthouse and no longer lives there.  And he also says he tried not getting involved with oversight of Alameda because of the "conflict of interest".

tweet: Sorkin asks about an interview Sam gave this summer where he said that FTX and Alameda are completely separate, with no shared personnel.   He also asks Sam if he still lives with members of Alameda in his penthouse
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: Sam emphasizes that he had little to do with Alameda and keeps referring to the fund as "them" instead of "we" (classic distancing language)  He says that he made a mistake with oversight, but doesn't know what happened besides that.

tweet: Sam nervously fidgets and takes a sip of a Pamplemousse flavored LaCroix before answering.  "I didn't knowingly comingle funds."

tweet: 22/ The recession is coming - and it will be interest rate induced.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 21/ We typically see this first wave of layoffs start ~12 months from the first hikes.  Then as it builds into a material amount of the labor force, the associated reduction in consumption due to lower income itself causes other industries to do layoffs & the effect can snowball.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 20/ For corporations, as the cost of capital increases, they will need to start ‚Äúprotecting their bottom lines,‚Äù as I outlined last week, by letting go of employers.  This is also paired with the pressure from equity markets to shorten duration in a high interest rate market.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 19/ As home equity turns over, so does purchasing home fixtures, electronics, and renovation materials.  When consumers buy homes they are also frequently moving ‚Äúout of the core,‚Äù thus requiring a car to commute.  Autos sales start to drop.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 18/ Rents are also going up because those priced out of buying are forced to rent.  Everyone is getting squeezed.  The result is lower disposable income to spend on discretionary items.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 17/ ...paying more on a monthly basis to preserve principal repayments (lower disposable income), or keeping the same payments, with a majority of the portion going towards interest rather than principal repayment (lower equity accumulation).
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 16/ It takes a while to reflect in price because those who thought about selling to ‚Äúmove up‚Äù are hesitant to do so because they will have to renew their mortgage at higher rates.  Those with variable mortgage rates are either extending their amortization‚Ä¶
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 15/ Rate hikes affect borrowers‚Äô ability to qualify for mortgages as the average 30yr mortgage moves with fed rates.  This means lower demand.  The White line shows the average 30yr mortgage rate while the yellow line shows the midpoint of the federal funds target rate.  https://t.co/5iwtkq7Coo
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 14/ Since the primary residence is the largest asset among households across various age groups (with the exception of the 55-64 demographic), changes in the value of this asset have an outsized impact on overall wealth - both real and perceived.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 13/ This is where we are today.  This rapid rise in interest rates takes time to work itself through the economy, typically with a 12-18 month lag.  The greatest consumer wealth shift going on right now is in the housing market.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 12/ But too much too quickly was never going to end well.  The morphine eventually wore off and we are now experiencing that hangover.  When rampant inflation started to come after this stimulus, the only thing the Fed could do was raise rates to get prices back in line.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 11/ Then Covid cops came and abruptly broke up the party.  Covid ground everything to a halt and stopped the economy in its tracks.  The Fed had to step in.  They did this in a huge way by drastically increasing the money supply to backstop the falloff in economic activity.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 10/ During the growth cycle, the Fed kept interest rates near zero for a long period.  The lower cost of lending spurred economic activity by forcing allocators of capital to focus on growth.  This crowded capital across every asset class as the bubble of everything inflated.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 9/ Coming back from their vacations, the consumer is faced with rising inflation, mortgage rates blowing through the roof, and the bill at dinner after a night out hitting a lot harder than it usually does.  This is all due to rates.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 8/ As lockdowns eased, the consumer shot out of the cannon as they sat on top a mountain of free money given to them by the government and spent it traveling to the Amalfi coast.  Now, people are starting to feel the hangover from too many Negroni Sbagliato‚Äôs.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 7/ ‚Ä¶we renovated our homes, bought everything with 1-day delivery on Amazon, binged on streaming services, and spent way too much money on new Fortnite skins.  We bought more things and did less things.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 6/ As consumers were locked away, they fired up Zoom for everything from meetings, poker nights, and the most depressing of them all‚Ä¶children‚Äôs birthday parties.  Instead of packing ourselves onto contaminated Petri dishes that are also known as cruise ships‚Ä¶
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 5/ Money was cheap and fast.  During this time, the consumer was feeling good, all the time.  Then came desolation and despair.  As the lockdown ensued, fundamental sea changes that would take decades to entrench, happened in months.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 4/ Before Covid, the consumer had a healthy spending mix between goods and services.  They did things and they bought things.  In this whimsical period, we had historically low-interest rates, equity markets were rocking & rolling, and the housing market was a no-lose scenario.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 3/ But just how strong are those affinities when other costs (like mortgages!) are continuing to ramp?  While inflation makes carrying $100 of groceries much easier, it also is eating significantly into the health of overall consumer spending.  Let‚Äôs recap how we got here.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: 2/ Someone needs to tell the consumer we‚Äôre heading for a recession.  Americans have a near insatiable need to buy ‚Äúthings.‚Äù Iconic brands - Nike, Apple, Coke.  All staples in the American persona.  Warren Buffett calls this obsession with image a moat through brand identity.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: While the cat is out of the bag on inflation - it's the ‚Äúbeast we know.‚Äù  We can see it.  We can feel it.  There has been a narrative that some point to a silver lining in a strong job market and a strong consumer.  These are both about to be very wrong conclusions.  üßµüëá
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA

tweet: FTX US and FTX were supposed to be legally separate: FTX US was supposed to keep American money separately held and not intermingle it with FTX International money.  If they did, that would basically defeat the purpose of this arrangement.

tweet: Let me first clarify what FTX US even is. FTX was forced to create a separate version of its exchange to comply with US securities regulations.  The original FTX exchange was not allowed to operate in the US, so FTX made a US-compliant version, FTX US.
name: Genevieve Roch-Decter, CFA
